      "side": 1,
      "message": "Have you considered the NaN tagged approach here?  8 aligned bytes that represent a double, and different NaN values represent the remaining tagged values.\n\nif (v as double \u003d\u003d v as double) {\n   type is Number\n} else {\n   switch (the 3 bits nearest the exponent) {\n       case 0: (unused, will explain)\n       case 1: null\n       case 2: bool\n       case 3: short string\n       case 4: long string\n       case 5: array\n       case 6: object\n       case 7: (available)\n   }\n}\n\nA double has a sign bit, 11 exponent bits, and 52 mantissa bits.  If you use the top 3 mantissa bits for the type tag when NaN, you\u0027ve got 49 left for payload.  Or make it an even 4 and 48, 6 bytes for the payload.  Even on 64-bit machines pointers fit in 6 bytes.\n\nI\u0027d avoid using tag 0 just to make sure you stay well far away from accidentally creating Infinity, which has the same exponent as NaN but all zero mantissa.",
